==English==

===Etymology===
From {{OF.}} {{term|cresme}} (modern: ''[[crème]]''), blend of {{LL.}} {{term|chrisma}} "ointment" (from {{Gk.}} {{term|chrisma}} "unguent"), and {{LL.}} {{term|cramum}} "cream", perhaps from {{Gau.}}. Replaced {{OE.}} ''ream''. Borrowed again from {{F.}} in the 1800s, as {{term|creme}}. Figurative sense of "most excellent element or part" appears from 1581. Verb meaning "to beat, thrash, wreck" is 1929, U.S. colloquial.

